title: Grateful Dead Live at The Palladium on 1977-05-01
description:
Set 1

Might As Well, El Paso, Ramble On Rose, Cassidy, They Love Each Other, Lazy Lightning-> Supplication, It Must Have Been The Roses, Estimated Prophet, Tennessee Jed, Sunrise, Samson & Delilah

Set 2

Dancin' In The Streets-> Brown Eyed Women, Beer Barrel Polka-> Playin' In The Band-> Drums-> The Other One-> Comes A Time-> Playing in the Band, E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: Hear that Spring '77 Magic Starting to Come Together Nice recording of a very good show. The Jerry tunes in the first set are just soooo groovy. Ramble on Rose and TLEO particularly stand out. Sunrise - I'm sorry, I like Donna Jean, but not a fan of this tune. Very cool Playin' sandwich to wrap up the second set, with the jam out of Comes a Time into the Reprise a highlight. Brokedown is the cherry on top. Thanks to all involved for making this available.
sunrise /never miss one comes a time  has been my life   empty cup  only love can feel

cant miss show wow 1977 is looking good on the grateful dead. donna fucking shines. hearing more from keith and some amazing keith/jer passages. sunrise blows me away. 1st of the year, donna is on, crowd loved it, great set closer. never cared for that song much before but im sold now. the new material is really settling into the repretoire and the crowd is with it. this is a great example of a show where you can clearly see the back n forth btwn crowd and band directing the show. grateful fucking dead.
 love the second set bew. historic grateful dead from playin on. a more subdued brokedown but 5 star performance from jer and ncreible way to close thhe night. cant wait to see how the energy goes into closing night of this run.
its unreal to listen night by night and watch the band changing, gelling, refining.

This is what we are talking about! 
Excellent aud from a stellar period. So much of this era has been released officially by Dick & Dave, it's fun to find an under the radar show from the same run, just a week before the mighty Barton Hall. 5/18 from Atlanta also one of the last under the radar shows out there.
